{
  "texts": [
    "If θ𝑑 is an isomorphism, a diagram chase will show that 𝜃 𝑑: 𝑅 Q (𝑑) → Q 𝑑 is injective and hence an isomorphism as desired.The element [𝜆 𝑑] is in the kernel of 𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑-1) ⊗ Q, hence (𝜃 𝑑-1 • 𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑-1) ⊗ Q) [𝜆 𝑑] = 0, and so, by commutativity of the above square, 𝜃 𝑑 [𝜆 𝑑] is in the kernel of (𝑖 𝑑-1) *.",
    "Since 𝜃 𝑑 [𝜆 𝑑] = (0,..., 0, 𝑑!)",
    "the map θ𝑑 is non-zero and it is therefore surjective as the projection onto the first (𝑑 -1) factors, (𝑖 𝑑-1) *: Q 𝑑 → Q 𝑑-1 has ker((𝑖 𝑑-1) *) Q.To show that the map on kernels is an isomorphism, we will show that both kernels have the same dimension.",
    "By the Yoneda lemma and the universal property of the excisive approximations the exact sequenceker(𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑-1) ⊗ Q) -→ 𝑅 Q (𝑑) -→ 𝑅 Q (𝑑 -1),may be identified with the exact sequence𝜋 0 (𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S (S)) ⊗ Q -→ 𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S (S)) ⊗ Q -→ 𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S (S)) ⊗ Q,induced by the 𝑑-homogeneous fibre sequence of ℎ S evaluated at S. Computing 𝑑-homogenous layer of ℎ S, we see that𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S (S) ≃ (𝜕 𝑑 ℎ S ⊗ S ⊗𝑑) ℎΣ 𝑑 ≃ (S ⊗ S ⊗𝑑) ℎΣ 𝑑 ≃ S ⊗𝑑 ℎΣ 𝑑 ≃ Σ ∞ + 𝐵Σ 𝑑.",
    "It follows that 𝜋 0 (𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S (S)) ⊗ Q 𝜋 0 (Σ ∞ + 𝐵Σ 𝑑) ⊗ Q Q,and hence there is an isomorphism ker(𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑-1) ⊗ Q) Q."
